Add documentation to your class and methods please. If you type "///" above the method it will create a structure like this: 

        /// <summary>
        /// Returns true if assign exists with given empId and deptId
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="empId"> Unique identifer for an employee</param>
        /// <param name="deptId"> Unique identifier for a department</param>
        /// <returns></returns>
        // GET: api/Assigns/Check/assignData

If the parameters are very clear and you dont have a description for them remove the <param> line(s) to keep it looking clean.

You can use //#region in angular to organize your typescript into regions as well. Kevin usually recommends having something like the following

//#region public properties

//#region constructor and ng methods

//#region private methods

//#region event handlers

for this you would need, event handlers, constructor and ng methods, and public properties.
